<h1>Things You Should Check for When Buying a Second-Hand Electric Car</h1>
<p>With emission zones on the rise and the ban on diesel and petrol vehicles looming, the pressure to buy an electric car has become increasingly intense.&nbsp;</p>
<p>With new EV models ranging from &pound;30-40k, regardless of PCP finance, the thought of purchasing another vehicle - much different from your own - plus a charging point, is enough to put the frighteners on some buyers. But what about second-hand models?&nbsp;</p>
<p>For reconditioned electric cars, customers can save anything between &pound;2-10k and with the battery lasting around 10 - 20 years, it's safe to say that purchasing a used model is good value for money. Like all used cars, before purchasing there are a few things you&rsquo;ll need to consider to ensure you&rsquo;re getting the best for your liking, and money.&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Check the history&nbsp;</h2>
<p>Electric, petrol, diesel, regardless of the type of vehicle you&rsquo;re looking to purchase, always check the history.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Aside from the written mediums such as MOT certificates, service history and logbooks, buyers can also check the car history online for additional information. If you&rsquo;re looking to purchase from an accredited company, some offer data checks on reconditioned models.&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Consider who you&rsquo;re purchasing from&nbsp;</h2>
<p>When searching for a second-hand car, consider the pros and cons of who you&rsquo;re looking to buy from.&nbsp;</p>
<p>For private sales, there&rsquo;s more scope to negotiate price and opportunities to analyse the genuineness of the seller in person. Are they selling the car for natural reasons or do they keep beating around the bush when you&rsquo;re asking questions? Things like body language, condition of the car and its paperwork are all factors you can effectively judge before purchasing the vehicle.</p>
<p>From dealers, the one thing you can count on is a paper trail, something that can be disadvantageous for some private tradesman. From big-named dealers, you can guarantee rigorous checks and in some cases, generous warranty deals. Nonetheless, like private sellers, they vary greatly and what one company offers, can be next to nothing compared to someone like an independent. Top tip? Research your dealers. For extra reliability, look for local tradesmen who are deemed credible in your community.&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Check for battery deterioration&nbsp;</h2>
<p>Moving to the physicalities, a major factor to check before you <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><em><strong><a href="https://www.spoticar.co.uk/used-cars/used-electric-cars">buy a second-hand electric car</a></strong></em></span> is the battery. Although the battery power of an electric car is reported to last up to 20 years, deterioration (roughly) drops around 1-2% each year, depending on mileage, charging, etc. When capacity drops to less than 80%, that&rsquo;s when drivers may see a lag in performance.&nbsp;</p>
<p>If you purchase from a manufacturer, you should receive a battery condition report, nonetheless, some EVs do display the battery&rsquo;s health on the dashboard. Which moves us nicely on to our next tip.</p>
<h2>Research alternative models&nbsp;</h2>
<p>It&rsquo;s easy to type in &lsquo;best electric car models&rsquo; online, however always consider what you&rsquo;ll be using the car for. With electric vehicles, although their range is impressive, not all cars provide Tesla-esc technologies and some manufacturers have a higher reputation than others.&nbsp;</p>
<p>When viewing a second-hand car, although you must check for any wear or tear, research manufacturers&rsquo; recurring issues. If a vehicle is said to generally have faults with its range/battery life after so many years, then don&rsquo;t consider purchasing the older model. Salesmen, though not all, will persuade you to buy the vehicle you like the look of... it&rsquo;s their job after all. So, ensure you have options before you visit.&nbsp;</p>
<h3>Overview</h3>
<p>Before purchasing a second-hand electric car, there are many elements to take into consideration such as wear and tear, the credibility of the dealer, paperwork&hellip;steps you would usually take before purchasing a petrol/diesel. With EVs, however, one of the most important factors to check is the car&rsquo;s battery health. Aside from battery reports and dashboard intel, you can go the extra mile and pay extra for a battery assessment - something to regard if you&rsquo;re buying privately. Nonetheless, do your research on manufacturers! Even if all of the above is ticked, look for manufacturer issues. You don&rsquo;t want to be stuck three years down the line with a worn car that&rsquo;s hard to resell. Especially if you&rsquo;re buying it outright.</p>
